sec.p:
Intervention analysis is used to evaluate the impact of a particular event on a time series, comparing the pattern of the time series before and after the event. Different types of intervention can be performed; they can be abrupt or gradual, permanent or temporary (Tabachnick and Fidell, 2007). As we have seen with the observation of the time series of the four groups of claims (see Figure 8), important peaks appear but they decline immediately. No permanent or gradual effects can be observed. However, each time series shows the occurrence of some events having abrupt and short-term effects. As a consequence, only intervention analyses for abrupt and temporary effects will be undertaken. The impact of five events, already mentioned in our descriptive analysis, will be analysed. They are the
attacks of 9/11 (11 September 2001);
bombings in Madrid (11 March 2004);
bombings in London (7 July 2005);
murder of Theo Van Gogh (2 November 2004); and
escalation of the affair of the Danish cartoon of Mahomet (February 2006).
